description:
## Goal

Seal the off-heap binary abstraction inside one module. Change the SharedBin layout to support per-instance destructors. Make the MSO list intrusive (threaded through ProcBin's previously-wasted padding). Eliminate the leaked test instrumentation and the test serialisation mutex.

## SharedBin layout (new)

```rust
#[repr(C)]
pub struct SharedBin {
    pub refcount: crate::sync::AtomicUsize,                   // 8
    pub bit_len: u64,                                         // 8
    pub bytes_ptr: *const u8,                                 // 8
    pub bytes_len: usize,                                     // 8
    pub destructor: unsafe extern "C" fn(*mut SharedBin),     // 8
}  // 40 bytes total, 8-byte aligned. unsafe impl Send + Sync.
```

Replaces today's `Box<[u8]>` with raw `(bytes_ptr, bytes_len)` so the layout is uniform whether the bytes live on the heap or in `.rodata` (the latter lands in fz-q8d.2). `crate::sync::AtomicUsize` is a re-export that fz-q8d.3 will turn into the loom-or-std abstraction; for .1, it's just `std::sync::atomic::AtomicUsize` directly.

## Destructor functions (runtime)

```rust
pub unsafe extern "C" fn shared_bin_destructor_heap(p: *mut SharedBin) {
    let bin = unsafe { Box::from_raw(p) };
    let bytes = unsafe {
        Box::from_raw(std::slice::from_raw_parts_mut(
            bin.bytes_ptr as *mut u8, bin.bytes_len,
        ))
    };
    drop(bytes);
    drop(bin);
    LIVE_COUNT.fetch_sub(1, Relaxed);
}

pub unsafe extern "C" fn shared_bin_destructor_noop(_p: *mut SharedBin) {}
```

Both are `extern "C"` (stable ABI) and `#[unsafe(no_mangle)]` (so codegen in fz-q8d.2 can take their addresses by name). The heap destructor reconstructs both the bytes box and the SharedBin box; the noop is empty body.

## Retain / release (uniform polymorphism)

```rust
pub unsafe fn shared_bin_retain(p: *mut SharedBin) {
    debug_assert!(!p.is_null());
    let bin = unsafe { &*p };
    let old = bin.refcount.fetch_add(1, Relaxed);
    debug_assert!(old < usize::MAX / 2, "SharedBin refcount overflow");
}

pub unsafe fn shared_bin_release(p: *mut SharedBin) {
    debug_assert!(!p.is_null());
    let bin = unsafe { &*p };
    if bin.refcount.fetch_sub(1, Release) == 1 {
        fence(Acquire);
        unsafe { (bin.destructor)(p); }
    }
}
```

Single atomic op per retain/release, indirect call only at the moment of final release. No sentinel arithmetic, no two-step checks.

## SharedBinHandle (safe owning wrapper)

```rust
pub struct SharedBinHandle(NonNull<SharedBin>);

impl SharedBinHandle {
    pub fn from_bytes(bytes: &[u8], bit_len: u64) -> Self { /* alloc; no retain */ }
    pub unsafe fn retain_from_raw(p: *mut SharedBin) -> Self { /* retain + wrap */ }
    pub unsafe fn from_raw_already_retained(p: *mut SharedBin) -> Self { /* wrap, no retain */ }
    pub fn as_raw(&self) -> *mut SharedBin { /* expose for storage */ }
    pub fn into_raw(self) -> *mut SharedBin { /* consume without releasing */ }
    /* getters: bit_len, bytes_ptr, bytes_len */
}

impl Clone for SharedBinHandle { /* retain + wrap */ }
impl Drop for SharedBinHandle { /* release */ }
```

`alloc_procbin` consumes a handle via `into_raw`; refcount ownership transfers from handle to ProcBin/MSO. Drop is suppressed (via consumption).

## ProcBin newtype (safe accessor wrapper)

```rust
#[repr(transparent)]
pub struct ProcBin(NonNull<HeapHeader>);

impl ProcBin {
    pub fn bit_len(&self) -> u64 { /* via shared_ptr → SharedBin.bit_len */ }
    pub fn bytes_ptr(&self) -> *const u8 { /* via shared_ptr → SharedBin.bytes_ptr */ }
    pub fn bytes_len(&self) -> usize { /* via shared_ptr → SharedBin.bytes_len */ }
    pub fn shared_raw(&self) -> *mut SharedBin { /* read offset 16 */ }
    pub fn mso_next(&self) -> *mut HeapHeader { /* read offset 24 */ }
    pub fn mso_next_set(&self, next: *mut HeapHeader) { /* write offset 24 */ }
    pub fn as_raw(&self) -> *mut HeapHeader { /* unwrap */ }
}
```

All offset arithmetic lives in this newtype's methods. Code outside the procbin module never reads ProcBin offsets directly.

## ProcBin layout (revised)

```
offset  0..16   HeapHeader { kind = ProcBin, size_bytes = 32 }
offset 16..24   shared_ptr: *mut SharedBin
offset 24..32   mso_next: *mut HeapHeader            ← was padding
```

Same total size (32 bytes). The 8 bytes formerly zero are now the intrusive MSO list link. The Cheney forwarding overwrites bytes 0..16 of the header only; ProcBin payload at +16 and +24 is preserved verbatim in the to-space copy. MSO sweep can read mso_next from from-space ProcBins (forwarded or not) reliably.

## Intrusive MSO list

`Heap.mso_list: Vec<*mut HeapHeader>` → `Heap.mso_head: *mut HeapHeader`.

- `alloc_procbin(heap, handle)`: writes the new ProcBin's `mso_next = self.mso_head`, sets `self.mso_head = new_procbin`. O(1) push, no allocation.
- Post-Cheney MSO sweep:
  ```
  let mut new_head: *mut HeapHeader = null;
  let mut cur = self.mso_head;
  while !cur.is_null() {
      let next = ProcBin(cur).mso_next();  // read before potentially overwriting
      let kind = unsafe { (*cur).kind };
      if kind == FORWARDED_KIND {
          let to_space = read_fwd_ptr(cur);  // offset 8
          ProcBin(to_space).mso_next_set(new_head);
          new_head = to_space;
      } else {
          // Dead — release shared_ptr via destructor.
          unsafe { shared_bin_release(ProcBin(cur).shared_raw()); }
      }
      cur = next;
  }
  self.mso_head = new_head;
  ```
- `Heap::drop`: walk the chain, release each shared_raw. No Vec allocation, no per-entry indirection.

## alloc_procbin signature change

```rust
// runtime/src/procbin.rs
pub fn alloc_procbin(heap: &mut Heap, handle: SharedBinHandle) -> ProcBin {
    let p = heap.alloc(32);
    /* write header + shared_ptr + mso_next, push to chain */
    let raw = handle.into_raw();  // moves refcount ownership in
    /* ... */
    ProcBin::from_raw(p)
}
```

Safe signature. The `unsafe fn` on `Heap::alloc_procbin` is gone. Caller code becomes:

```rust
let handle = SharedBinHandle::from_bytes(bytes, bit_len);
let procbin = alloc_procbin(&mut heap, handle);
```

No unsafe blocks at call sites for the common path.

## Dispatch helpers move

`is_bitstring_like` / `bitstring_bit_len` / `bitstring_byte_ptr` move from `runtime/src/fz_value.rs` into the procbin module. Their signature stays the same (take `*const HeapHeader`, return what they return). `fz_value.rs::render_bitstring` and the four other read sites are updated to call the new module path.

## Test instrumentation cleanup

- `pub fn shared_bin_live_count()` → `pub(crate) fn live_count()`.
- `pub fn live_count_lock()` is **deleted**.
- All 12 call sites in `runtime/src/heap.rs` and `runtime/src/shared_bin.rs` unit tests are reworked to use baseline-delta without the lock. Two strategies:
  - For tests that allocate exactly N bins and free them in scope: track via Drop counters on RAII guards.
  - For tests that need a fixed baseline: use `serial_test = "3"` crate gating with `#[serial]` on the specific tests that need it. Add as a dev-dep on `fz-runtime`.
- Net: no globally-shared test mutex; serial-test gating only where the assertion semantics demands it.

## Changes by file

- `runtime/src/shared_bin.rs` → renamed to `runtime/src/procbin.rs`. Now owns both SharedBin and ProcBin.
- `runtime/src/lib.rs`: replace `pub mod shared_bin` with `pub mod procbin`. Optionally keep `pub use procbin as shared_bin` for one revision if external callers exist.
- `runtime/src/heap.rs`: 
  - Remove `pub unsafe fn alloc_procbin` (moves to procbin module as safe `alloc_procbin`)
  - Remove `pub fn procbin_shared_ptr`
  - Replace `mso_list: Vec<*mut HeapHeader>` with `mso_head: *mut HeapHeader`
  - Replace the in-place MSO sweep block with a call to `crate::procbin::mso_sweep(self)`
  - `Heap::drop` calls `crate::procbin::mso_drop_all(self)` before pool_free
  - `Heap::alloc_bitstring`: above-threshold path becomes `let h = SharedBinHandle::from_bytes(bytes, bit_len); alloc_procbin(self, h).as_raw()`. No more raw refcount.
  - `deep_copy_value`'s ProcBin arm: `let h = unsafe { SharedBinHandle::retain_from_raw(src_procbin.shared_raw()) }; let dp = alloc_procbin(dst_heap, h);`. No raw retain.
- `runtime/src/fz_value.rs`: remove `is_bitstring_like` / `bitstring_bit_len` / `bitstring_byte_ptr`. Update `render_bitstring` to import from `crate::procbin`.
- `runtime/src/ir_runtime.rs`: update `fz_bs_write_field`, `fz_bs_reader_init`, `fz_bs_read_field` to import dispatch helpers from `crate::procbin`.
- `runtime/Cargo.toml`: add `serial_test = "3"` as dev-dep if any tests need the gating.

## Tests

All existing unit tests in `shared_bin.rs` / `procbin.rs` and `heap.rs` continue to pass with the new API. Plus new tests:

- Destructor dispatch: alloc a SharedBin via `shared_bin_alloc`, observe its destructor field == `shared_bin_destructor_heap` symbol address. Force release-to-zero, observe LIVE_COUNT decremented.
- Custom destructor: construct a SharedBin manually with a test destructor that increments an `AtomicBool`. retain+release exactly to zero, observe the destructor fired exactly once.
- Intrusive MSO sweep: build a heap with 5 ProcBins, root 3 of them, run GC. Expect mso_head chain length 3, all entries pointing into to-space; LIVE_COUNT dropped by 2.
- SharedBinHandle Drop: allocate, clone (retain), drop both, observe destructor fires exactly once when the second Drop runs.
- Heap::drop: allocate 3 ProcBins, drop the heap, observe LIVE_COUNT dropped by 3.

## Acceptance

- Clippy and warnings clean.
- No `unsafe fn` in the new module's public API surface for the common allocation path (only the raw retain/release primitives stay unsafe — they're the unsafe building blocks the handle wraps).
- The integration fixture `fixtures/shared_heap_send_large_bitstring/` still passes across `[jit, interp, aot]`.
- 605+ existing tests continue to pass; new tests in this ticket pass.

## Non-changes

- `Heap::alloc_bitstring`'s threshold policy (64 bytes) is unchanged.
- The const-fold pass `src/ir_const_bs.rs` is unchanged (widened in .2).
- AOT shim and scheduler hooks unaffected.
